_much_	1
clearer;	1
but	1
I	1
still	1
don't	1
_quite_	1
understand--forgive	1
my	1
slow	1
mind--why	1
did	1
you	1
not	1
come	1
out,	1
by	1
yourself?"	1
"Can't	1
you	1
see	1
that	1
the	1
door	1
shut	1
me	1
in?"	1
said	1
the	1
Tiger.	1
"Oh,	1
I	1
do	1
beg	1
your	1
pardon,"	1
said	1
the	1
little	1
Jackal.	1
"I	1
know	1
I	1
am	1
very	1
slow;	1
I	1
can	1
never	1
understand	1
things	1
well	1
unless	1
I	1
see	1
just	1
how	1
they	1
were;	1
if	1
you	1
could	1
show	1
me	1
now	1
exactly	1
how	1
that	1
door	1
works	1
I	1
am	1
sure	1
I	1
could	1
understand.	1
How	1
does	1
it	1
shut?"	1
"It	1
shuts	1
like	1
this,"	1
said	1
the	1
Brahmin,	1
pushing	1
it	1
to.	1
"Yes;	1
but	1
I	1
don't	1
see	1
any	1
lock,"	1
said	1
the	1
little	1
Jackal,	1
"does	1
it	1
lock	1
on	1
the	1
outside?"	1
"It	1
locks	1
like	1
this,"	1
said	1
the	1
Brahmin.	1
And	1
he	1
shut	1
and	1
bolted	1
the	1
door!	1
"Oh,	1
does	1
it,	1
indeed?"	1
said	1
the	1
little	1
Jackal.	1
"Does	1
it,	1
_indeed_!	1
Well,	1
Brother	1
Brahmin,	1
now	1
that	1
it	1
is	1
locked,	1
I	1
should	1
advise	1
you	1
to	1
let	1
it	1
stay	1
locked!	1
As	1
for	1
you,	1
my	1
friend,"	1
he	1
said	1
to	1
the	1
Tiger,	1
"I	1
think	1
you	1
will	1
wait	1
a	1
good	1
while	1
before	1
you'll	1
find	1
anyone	1
to	1
let	1
you	1
out	1
again!"	1
Then	1
he	1
made	1
a	1
very	1
low	1
bow	1
to	1
the	1
Brahmin.	1
"Good-bye,	1
Brother,"	1
he	1
said.	1
"Your	1
way	1
lies	1
that	1
way,	1
and	1
mine	1
lies	1
this;	1
good-bye!"	1
THE	1
LITTLE	1
JACKAL	1
AND	1
THE	1
CAMEL	1
All	1
these	1
stories	1
about	1
the	1
little	1
Jackal	1
that	1
I	1
have	1
told	1
you,	1
show	1
how	1
clever	1
the	1
little	1
Jackal	1
was.	1
But	1
you	1
know--if	1
you	1
don't,	1
you	1
will	1
when	1
you	1
are	1
grown	1
up--that	1
no	1
matter	1
how	1
clever	1
you	1
are,	1
sooner	1
or	1
later	1
you	1
surely	1
meet	1
some	1
one	1
who	1
is	1
more	1
clever.	1
It	1
is	1
always	1
so	1
in	1
life.	1
And	1
it	1
was	1
so	1
with	1
the	1
little	1
Jackal.	1
This	1
is	1
what	1
happened.	1
The	1
little	1
Jackal	1
was,	1
as	1
you	1
know,	1
exceedingly	1
fond	1
of	1
shell-fish,	1
especially	1
of	1
river	1
crabs.	1
Now	1
there	1
came	1
a	1
time	1
when	1
he	1
had	1
eaten	1
all	1
the	1
crabs	1
to	1
be	1
found	1
on	1
his	1
own	1
side	1
of	1
the	1
river.	1
He	1
knew	1
there	1
must	1
be	1
plenty	1
on	1
the	1
other	1
side,	1
if	1
he	1
could	1
only	1
get	1
to	1
them,	1
but	1
he	1
could	1
not	1
swim.	1
One	1
day	1
he	1
thought	1
of	1
a	1
plan.	1
He	1
went	1
to	1
his	1
friend	1
the	1
Camel,	1
and	1
said,--	1
"Friend	1
Camel,	1
I	1
know	1
a	1
spot	1
where	1
the	1
sugar-cane	1
grows	1
thick;	1
I'll	1
show	1
you	1
the	1
way,	1
if	1
you	1
will	1
take	1
me	1
there."	1
"Indeed	1
I	1
will,"	1
said	1
the	1
Camel,	1
who	1
was	1
very	1
fond	1
of	1
sugar-cane.	1
"Where	1
is	1
it?"	1
"It	1
is	1
on	1
the	1
other	1
side	1
of	1
the	1
river,"	1
said	1
the	1
little	1
Jackal;	1
"but	1
we	1
can	1
manage	1
it	1
nicely,	1
if	1
you	1
will	1
take	1
me	1
on	1
your	1
back	1
and	1
swim	1
over."	1
The	1
Camel	1
was	1
perfectly	1
willing,	1
so	1
the	1
little	1
Jackal	1
jumped	1
on	1
his	1
back,	1
and	1
the	1
Camel	1
swam	1
across	1
the	1
river,	1
carrying	1
him.	1
When	1
they	1
were	1
safely	1
over,	1
the	1
little	1
Jackal	1
jumped	1
down	1
and	1
showed	1
the	1
Camel	1
the	1
sugar-cane	1
field;	1
then	1
he	1
ran	1
swiftly	1
along	1
the	1
river	1
bank,	1
to	1
hunt	1
for	1
crabs;	1
the	1
Camel	1
began	1
to	1
eat	1
sugar-cane.	1
He	1
ate	1
happily,	1
and	1
noticed	1
nothing	1
around	1
him.	1
Now,	1
you	1
know,	1
a	1
Camel	1
is	1
very	1
big,	1
and	1
a	1
Jackal	1
is	1
very	1
little.	1
Consequently,	1
the	1
little	1
Jackal	1
had	1
eaten	1
his	1
fill	1
by	1
the	1
time	1
the	1
Camel	1
had	1
barely	1
taken	1
a	1
mouthful.	1
The	1
little	1
Jackal	1
had	1
no	1
mind	1
to	1
wait	1
for	1
his	1
slow	1
friend;	1
he	1
