we	1
call	1
"irrigating";	1
and	1
they	1
planted	1
enough	1
corn	1
and	1
grain	1
and	1
vegetables	1
for	1
all	1
the	1
people.	1
Every	1
one	1
helped,	1
and	1
every	1
one	1
watched	1
for	1
the	1
sprouting,	1
with	1
hopes,	1
and	1
prayers,	1
and	1
careful	1
eyes.	1
In	1
good	1
time	1
the	1
seeds	1
sprouted,	1
and	1
the	1
dry,	1
brown	1
earth	1
was	1
covered	1
with	1
a	1
carpet	1
of	1
tender,	1
green,	1
growing	1
things.	1
No	1
farmer's	1
garden	1
could	1
have	1
looked	1
better	1
than	1
the	1
great	1
garden	1
of	1
the	1
desert	1
valley.	1
And	1
from	1
day	1
to	1
day	1
the	1
little	1
shoots	1
grew	1
and	1
flourished	1
till	1
they	1
were	1
all	1
well	1
above	1
the	1
ground.	1
Then	1
a	1
terrible	1
thing	1
happened.	1
One	1
day,	1
the	1
men	1
who	1
were	1
watering	1
the	1
crops	1
saw	1
a	1
great	1
number	1
of	1
crickets	1
swarming	1
over	1
the	1
ground	1
at	1
the	1
edge	1
of	1
the	1
gardens	1
nearest	1
the	1
mountains.	1
They	1
were	1
hopping	1
from	1
the	1
barren	1
places	1
into	1
the	1
young,	1
green	1
crops,	1
and	1
as	1
they	1
settled	1
down	1
they	1
